<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1923-09-04T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1923-09-02T11:00:00-05:00" n="397" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d397">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">894.48B/3: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Woods</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi><note n="22" xml:id="d397fn22">This message was the first report to the
                                Department by the Ambassador in Japan after the earthquake. It was
                                sent Sept. 2 by radio from a Japanese warship.</note></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Iwaki</hi></placeName> [<date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content-and-sibling-dates" calendar="gregorian" notAfter="1923-09-04T23:59:59-05:00" notBefore="1923-09-02T12:00:00-04:00"><hi rend="italic">undated</hi></date>].<lb/>[Received September 4, 1923—3:21
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>All Americans believed safe. All Embassy buildings totally destroyed but
                            no one in Embassy injured. Food situation very acute. Send rations at
                            once from Philippines.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Woods</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>